 We use the approach that we’ve seen many times before: first find an equation of the line of the requisite type and then use it to make the necessary computation.
The line passes through $(5, 10)$, and we could fit it with an equation $y = mx + b$ for some real numbers $m$ and $b$.  This is done by computing $m = (10 - 6)/5 = 2/5$, the slope of the line passing through $(0,6)$ and $(5,10)$.  In other words,
\begin{align*}
m &= \dfrac{10-6}{5-0} = \dfrac{10-6}{5}\\
&=\dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x} = \mbox{Slope of the line}.
\end{align*}
This simplifies to $m = 2/5$.  As well, we know,
\begin{align*}
b&=10-m(5)\\
&=10-2/5(5)\\
&=10-(2)(1)\\
&=\boxed{8}
\end{align*}
but only needed the last line. In other words, $b = 8$.  Therefore, the line in question is of the form $y = (2/5)x + 8$.  
We are required to compute the $y$-coordinate of the point this line crosses the $y$-axis.  This happens at $x = 0$, since if $x$ is increased, $(2/5)x$ is too.  Plugging this value in, we have $y = 8$, which is the answer.
